<TEXT>
the reagan administration is considering 
withholding governmental benefits such as student loans and public 
housing assistance to people convicted of drug use according to a 
published report 
the cabinetlevel national drug policy board headed by attorney 
general edwin meese iii approved the proposals in outline form at a 
meeting may 27 but they have not yet been presented to president 
reagan the washington post reported in wednesdays editions citing 
sources it did not identify 
were not trying to be draconian were not going to kick poor 
people out of public housing the post quoted one source as 
saying but at the same time were trying to encourage state 
and local governments and colleges to adopt antidrug programs that 
will have maximum impact 
the proposals would seek to fight drug abuse by threatening to 
withhold some federal aid to state and local governments colleges 
and universities and other publicly funded institutions that fail to 
adopt strict federally approved antidrug programs the sources 
said 
one proposal calls for state governments to refuse to issue 
firsttime drivers licenses to minors who have been convicted of 
drug use and the federal government would enforce this by 
threatening to withhold federal transportation funding the post 
said 
various federal department and agencies were directed to study 
the proposals and report back to meese by wednesday the newspaper 
said one source told the post that no objections had been raised 
and that the proposals probably would be presented to reagan within 
the next few days 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

