<TEXT>
the dean of the district of columbia law school 
has resigned two months after his selection and three months before 
classes are scheduled to begin according to a published report 
it was the most agonizing decision of my career frank n 
jones told the washington post for a story in tuesdays editions 
my wife and family decided they really didnt want to move its 
as simple as that 
jones resignation becomes effective june 15 he plans to return 
to a private law practice in boston where he lives with his wife 
who is also an attorney and two children 
the resignation is the most recent in a series of setbacks that 
have plagued the fledgling law school created amid controversy over 
whether the city should take over its predecessor the failing 
antioch school of law 
mayor marion barry and the board of directors of the university 
of the district of columbia which is to assume control of the 
school in two years have opposed the takeover 
board chairman frederick b abramson said jones resignation 
makes it difficult to continue the schools operations because 
jones was responsible for many of the startup activities 
the resignation also adds to the growing list of law school deans 
in washington and around the nation who have quit recently 
in may the law school deans at american university and 
georgetown university announced their resignations meanwhile 
george washington university law school named a new dean in april 
and new deans have assumed positions at the law schools of catholic 
and howard universities in the past two years the george mason 
university law school in suburban arlington va also named a new 
dean in the last two years 
the american bar association has reported that 86 of the nations 
174 abaapproved law schools hired new deans in the last three 
years and the average tenure has declined from six years to 32 
years 
</TEXT>
