<TEXT>
concern over the hazards of chemical pesticides 
has gone too far according to members of a farm womens 
organization meeting in the nations capital 
we feed our families with the food we grow were not going to 
feed them poison says mildred brown of hale center texas 
she is here for the sixth annual washington meeting of women 
involved in farm economics an organization that brings together 
farm women from across the country to wrestle with agricultural 
issues 
the group frequently has focused on the intricacies of world 
markets for farm commodities and federal payment programs but 
pressure for congressional action on the pesticide issue prompted an 
environmental seminar as well this year 
many crops produced in the united states and overseas are sprayed 
with pesticides some of which the us environmental protection 
agency has linked with cancer and other serious health problems 
the two speakers at the farm womens session were representatives 
of industries that have been major targets of environmental 
criticism 
jack early president of the national agricultural chemical 
association focused on pesticides while vickie sullivan a 
legislative analyst with a utility company discussed the acid rain 
issue 
early said he doubted that regulatory legislation recently 
produced by the senate agriculture committee would be sent to the 
presidents desk this year 
he said so many loose ends remain to be tied up in other 
committees that it will be close to impossible to get all these 
things pulled together 
to do all that before congress goes home and tries to get 
reelected and they will do that earlier this year i just dont 
think you can get it all done this year he said 
his organization is supporting the agriculture committees bill 
but is opposing separate legislation cosponsored by agriculture 
committee chairman patrick j leahy dvt and sen david 
durenberger rminn 
it would impose stringent standards for clean groundwater which 
provides the major supply of drinking water for millions of 
americans but has in some areas been found to be laced with 
pesticides 
there may be an effort to attach the leahydurenberger plan to 
the agriculture committees blueprint for revising the federal 
insecticide fungicide and rodenticide act 
after the session a number of members of the farm womens group 
agreed to discuss their attitudes toward pesticides at an impromptu 
roundtable discussion 
alice parker the groups president recalled how she drove into 
a farmers market near her home town of royal city wash not long 
ago with a truckload of vegetables nearby another farmer was 
parked advertising that his vegetables were organically grown 
without the use of pesticides 
customers were interested at first she says but that changed 
he had on his truck organicially grown and as soon as they 
found the worms on his vegetables they walked away she recalled 
they want absolutely perfect products and we have supplied them 
with them said naioma benson of sterling colo a wheat and 
cattle producer 
environmentalists she said are not looking at the total full 
picture and often have a biased and slanted view the notion 
that farmers are poisoning the land with toxic chemicals is absurd 
she said 
our families depend on it our futures and our childrens 
futures depend on it 
my husband really respects the chemicals and is very careful 
how he uses them said merlina tate of almira wash she also 
recalled a trip to the soviet union last year to inspect irrigation 
systems used in that country she saw beautiful vegetables grown 
there without benefit of pesticides 
but those same vegetables would not be bought in a us 
store she said the reason too many flaws caused by pests 
the women condemned the notion that us law should attempt to 
eliminate all risk from the use of pesticides 
instead they said pesticide use should be likened to the use of 
certain drugs that are beneficial in treating illnesses but 
sometimes have side effects or to automobiles which are certain to 
mean highway fatalities but provide vital transportation 
they also pointed the finger at pesticides banned here that are 
being used overseas on crops that are then brought into this country 
theyre being used in mexico and hauled across the border 
said clara jo spivey a louisville ala cotton and peanut grower 
</TEXT>
