defense secretary frank c carlucci praised the 
japanese government for taking on a greater share of its own 
defense but urged it to contribute more toward western security 
speaking to the japan national press club on monday carlucci 
noted that japan has in this decade taken on defense of sealanes up 
to 1000 miles offshore and begun a fiveyear procurement plan of 
beefing up its forces 
he said japan had done away with its selfimposed limit of 
spending just 1 percent of its gross national product on defense and 
that the government had also pledged to pay all nonsalary 
allowances and expenses for japanese workers on us bases here by 
1990 
japan does more than it often gets credit for he said i 
want to make equally clear today that still more remains to be 
done 
carlucci urged japan to increase defense spending since the 
current program provides for what he called the minimum capability 
japan needs to fulfill the defense obligations it has assumed 
japan also should increase its financial support for maintaining 
us military personnel stationed here which costs the us 
government 3 billion annually he said 
carlucci also called on japan to boost overseas economic aid to 
such developing nations such as pakistan portugal turkey and 
afghanistan which he called nations in which aid could advance 
our overall security 
he said the west should strengthen controls on its exports to the 
east to keep its technological lead over the soviet bloc and should 
not be lulled by last weeks superpower summit in moscow 
until we see some tangible changes we should not change our 
policies he said we are still facing a serious military 
