<TEXT>
hashemi rafsanjani was reelected speaker 
of irans parliament today consolidating his hold on political and 
military power 
rafsanjanis reelection came five days after ayatollah ruhollah 
khomeini named him commanderinchief of the armed forces in the 
wake of two major battlefield defeats in the war against iraq 
irans official islamic republic news agency monitored in 
nicosia said 187 of the 192 parliamentary deputies whose 
credentials have been approved since elections in april and may 
voted for rafsanjani five abstained 
rafsanjani 53 has been speaker since 1980 
radicals including many rafsanjani supporters made sweeping 
gains in the elections at the expense of conservatives who have 
blocked economic reforms 
the credentials of other elected deputies in the 270seat majlis 
or parliament have either been passed to an investigating committee 
for scrutiny following objections from other deputies or have not 
yet been approved irna reported 
rafsanjani is also khomeinis representative on the supreme 
defense council which determines irans strategy in the 7year war 
with iraq he sits on the council for the expediency of state 
decrees formed earlier this year by khomeini to push radical 
economic reforms through parliament 
rafsanjani has strong links with the revolutionary guards corps 
which is now more powerful than the iranian army 
the 87yearold khomeini patriarch of irans islamic revolution 
has been reported in poor health speculation that his condition was 
deteriorating was heightened when he relinquished his constitutional 
position as commanderinchief to rafsanjani a middleranking 
cleric 
khomeini has designated a senior cleric ayatollah husseinali 
montazeri as his successor but many leading figures including 
rafsanjani oppose montazeri 
khomeinis appointment underlined that rafsanjani who has long 
been close to the patriarch retains his confidence and is being 
groomed to hold great power in the postkhomeini era 
the election was the most fiercely contested since the islamic 
revolution toppled the shah mohammad reza pahlavi in 1979 the gains 
in parliament by the radicals supported by khomeini prompted 
allegations by some prominent conservatives who failed to win 
reelection that the polling was rigged 
it sharpened divisions between radicals seeking a centralized 
staterun economy and the conservatives who are backed by the 
wealthy merchant class 
the elections touched off clashes between khomeini supporters 
backed by the revolutionary guards and protesters in several cities 
diplomatic sources reported several people were reported killed 
when the guards opened fire on demonstrators 
irans best known opposition politician former prime minister 
mehdi bazargan distributed an open letter last week accusing 
khomeini of erroneous policies in the war with iraq and making 
the islamic republic an object of hate around the world 
reports reaching paris said bazargans criticism triggered a wave 
of arrests but it was not known if bazargan himself had been 
detained 
bazargans small freedom movement is the only opposition faction 
permitted to function openly in iran and has been constantly 
harassed by khomeini militants in recent years 
