last week to assess the situation but no meetings were held with 
noriega or other government officials 
abrams said morton abramowitz head of the bureau of intelligence 
and research explored the possibility of new us options for 
dealing with panama in the wake of the failed negotiating effort 
paul taylor a deputy assistant secretary who accompanied 
abramowitz examined the us sanctions against panama and concluded 
that the economic pressures on panama are very great abrams 
said 
among other measures the administration has frozen panamanian 
assets in the united states and is withholding payments to panama 
for services related to the operation of the panama canal 
a separate latin american initiative on panama involves an offer 
by guatemalan president vinicio cerezo for his country to be used as 
a site for negotiations between noriega and his political opponents 
abrams appeared to hold out little hope that any latin american 
negotiation could reach a settlement that would meet the us goal 
of restoring democracy in panama 
