<TEXT>
while environmentalists waited for a judge to 
consider their request to stop the navy from generating intense 
electromagnetic pulses off the atlantic coast the pentagon 
announced today that the tests had begun 
the tests according to the navy are intended to measure the 
ability of naval equipment to withstand radiation following a 
nuclear blast 
the pentagon said the empress ii barge had reached the test site 
off the virginianorth carolina coast monday afternoon and began the 
monthlong experiment by transmitting three microsecond bursts of 
electrical energy at around 4 pm 
at about 8 am this morning the generator began the second day 
of tests said lt karen kent a navy spokeswoman in washington 
the tests she said were being monitored by sophisticated measuring 
devices onshore 15 miles away 
the effect of the transmissions at those sites would be the 
same as sitting inside a car and transmitting on a cb radio for one 
second she said 
the foundation on economic trends a washingtonbased 
environmental group asked the us appeals court for the district 
of columbia on monday to halt the project 
right now our attorneys are at the courthouse trying to get the 
judge to set a time for a hearing on our request for an injunction 
while we appeal the last court ruling said jeremy rifkin 
director of the foundation 
the barge empress ii is designed to simulate the electromagnetic 
radiation that would follow the detonation of a nuclear weapon 
outside the earths atmosphere the tests are intended to determine 
the ability of navy ships aircraft and weapons to withstand the 
pulses 
empress ii or electromagnetic pulse radiation environment 
simulator for ships second generation can generate pulses of up to 
7 million volts 
environmentalists have expressed concern the surges will disrupt 
the marine environment within the test area and might affect 
computers and other delicate equipment outside it 
we just do not believe the navy has taken a hard look at these 
possible consequences at this particular site said andrew 
kimbrell an attorney for the foundation 
the foundation filed a lawsuit in 1987 and reached agreement with 
the navy last month that an environmental impact statement was 
needed before testing could begin 
the foundations interpretation of the agreement was that the 
navy would submit an environmental impact statement on the site it 
chose for testing which could take up to two years 
the navys interpretation was that it would submit an impact 
statement but that the study would not necessarily involve a 
specific site the navy submitted a statement previously drawn up 
for a chesapeake bay site 
a federal judge ruled friday that the navys interpretation was 
plausible and allowed the tests to proceed several calls today to 
the pentagon seeking to find out the time for the tests were not 
returned 
the navy insists that no dangers to the environment have been 
found in 20 years of similar testing and exhaustive studies 
</TEXT>
