<TEXT>
drug experiments on more than 200 pregnant women 
were known to the president of the cook county board but he did not 
tell other commissioners according to the director of the county 
hospital 
two doctors gave dilantin a drug commonly used to treat 
epilepsy to about 245 pregnant women to determine whether the drug 
reduced fetal stress during caesareansection births hospital 
director terrence hansen said 
but only five of the women had consented to participate in the 
hospitalapproved study that began in september 1987 he said 
hansen and other hospital officials met with the board which 
acts as trustees for the hospital behind closed doors for nearly 
two hours monday to discuss the case against the two 
anesthesiologists 
several board members said they were angry and shocked when they 
heard the disclosure the boards president george dunne said he 
didnt recall being told 
he said the board would take no immediate action and would wait 
for the hospital medical staffs executive committee to finish its 
investigation a process required under medical staff bylaws 
hansen said dunne was told about the experiments in january when 
hospital medical director dr agnes lattimer ordered a halt to the 
study 
we told president dunne and he advised us to follow due process 
according to the hospitals bylaws hansen said 
dunne said i dont recall that conversation 
commissioner samuel vaughan head of the health and hospitals 
committee which oversees county oak forest and cermak hospitals 
said doctors should know that you dont conduct experiments on 
patients without getting their consent 
hansen said the doctors study called for giving the drug to no 
more than 50 pregnant patients who were candidates for 
caesareansection deliveries 
the great majority of the 245 patients given the drug were 
pregnant hansen said adding that he knew at least one patient 
who was not 
he said he was not sure why nonpregnant women would have been 
given dilantin 
several past studies have reported higher incidences of birth 
defects including heart abnormalities and retardation in babies 
born to women who regularly used dilantin and other drugs used to 
combat epileptic seizures 
hansen has noted however that the women at cook county hospital 
were given a single dose of between 500 and 700 milligrams 
substantially lower than a normal dose at or near the time 
they delivered 
ms lattimer said she was convinced the pregnant women who had 
been given the drug without their consent suffered no adverse 
effects 
that does not mean it is not a serious infraction and should 
not be prevented from happening again she said the physicians 
involved in this study violated hospital regulations 
