<TEXT>
the national highway traffic safety 
administration acted reasonably in lowering mandatory fuel economy 
standards to 26 miles per gallon a federal appeals court ruled 
21 tuesday 
nhtsa lowered the corporate average fuel economy or cafe 
standard automakers must meet in 1986 from the 275 mpg set by 
congress to 26 mpg asserting the higher standard was not 
economically practical 
the state of california the cities of los angeles and new york 
and four citizens groups led by washingtonbased public citizen 
filed petitions requesting a court review of the order 
the us court of appeals for the district of columbia circuit 
in an opinion by judge ruth ginsburg said nhtsas consideration 
of the likelihood of economic hardship within its assessment of 
economic practicability must be given due weight 
the agencys decision was based on analysis that concluded the 
higher standard would have severe economic effects throughout the 
auto industry and therefore was not arbitrary or capricious as the 
petitioners had charged the court said 
the petitioners also asserted that nhtsa by lowering the 
standard had failed to consider the nations need to conserve 
energy the cafe standards were initially adopted in the 1970s to 
reduce us dependence on foreign oil 
the court however said the agency had weighed increased fuel 
consumption against economic harm under broad guidelines set by 
congress 
had congress offered a more precise balancing formula for the 
agency to apply we could more confidently discern the agencys 
compliance with the congressional mandate the court said 
in the absence of such precision the court said it must conclude 
nhtsa had properly accomodated conflicting policies in lowering the 
standard 
mrs ginsbug was joined in the majority by judge abner mikva 
judge lawrence silberman dissented 
transportation secretary jim burnley has called for repeal of the 
cafe standards saying in an era of cheaper energy they have 
outlived their usefulness and harm the us auto industrys 
competitiveness 
supporters of the standards argue they must be retained to keep 
the nation from again slipping into deep dependence on unreliable 
foreign sources of oil 
besides nhtsa the petitions named ford motor co the automobile 
importers of america inc and general motors corp as defendants 
</TEXT>
