<TEXT>
irans parliament reelected hashemi 
rafsanjani as its speaker on tuesday cementing his political and 
military power parliament voted in a firebrand cleric as 
rafsanjanis deputy 
rafsanjanis reelection to the key position came only five days 
after ayatollah ruhollah khomeini named him commanderinchief of 
the countrys armed forces that appointment followed two serious 
military defeats for iran in the nearly 8yearold iraniraq war 
irans official islamic republic news agency monitored in 
nicosia reported that 187 of the 192 parliamentary deputies whose 
credentials had been approved since elections in april and may voted 
for rafsanjani five abstained 
radicals many of them rafsanjani supporters made sweeping gains 
in the elections at the expense of conservatives who have blocked 
economic reforms 
the elction sharpened divisions between radicals who seek a 
centralized staterun economy and the conservatives who are backed 
by the bazaaris the wealthy merchant class 
rafsanjani 53 was named temporary speaker when the parliament 
or majlis convened may 28 pending a twothirds quorum to elect a 
permanent speaker he has been speaker since 1980 
the majlis also elected two deputy speakers tuesday irna 
reported 
one is hojatoleslam mehdi karroubi a middleranking cleric who 
is the militant head of the pilgrimage bureau and believed to have 
been responsible for masterminding riots by iranian pilgrims in the 
holy moslem city of mecca last year hundreds of people died in the 
riots 
the other is hussein hashemian a littleknown deputy from 
rafsanjanis hometown of rafsanjan in southeast iran 
rafsanjanis reelection appeared to set the seal on his 
political power 
he is already khomeinis representative on the supreme defense 
council which determines irans strategy in the war he sits on the 
council for the expediency of state decrees formed earlier this 
year by khomeini to push radical economic reforms through parliament 
rafsanjani also has strong links with the revolutionary guards 
corps which is now more powerful than the iranian army and leader 
of the clerics who deliver sermons at the weekly friday prayer 
sessions in tehran an influential religious and political platform 
rafsanjanis widening power leaves him wellplaced to become the 
kingmaker in the power struggle among irans fractious leadership 
that is expected to swell when khomeini dies 
the 87yearold revolutionary patriarch has been reported in poor 
health speculation that his condition was deteriorating was 
heightened when he relinquished his constitutional position as 
commanderinchief to rafsanjani a middleranking cleric 
there has been no hard evidence to support that but the new york 
times reported that some us officials believe rafsanjanis 
appointment indicated khomeini may no longer be capable or willing 
to continue to run military affairs 
khomeini has designated a senior cleric ayatollah husseinali 
montazeri as his successor 
but montazari is opposed by many leading figures and is widely 
expected to be little more than figurehead for a small group of 
political heavyweights led by the charismatic rafsanjani after 
khomeini dies 
khomeinis appointment of rafsanjani long a close aide as 
military leader underlined that rafsanjani has his confidence and is 
apparently being groomed to hold the reins of power in the critical 
era that will follow khomeinis death 
rafsanjani is also close to khomeinis son and confidant ahmed 
