<TEXT>
the soviet union could launch nucleartipped 
rockets that would threaten to knock out the proposed earlyround 
version of president reagans star wars antimissile system a 
scientific study said tuesday 
the us system also would be threatened by the possibility that 
the enormously complex software needed to run its computers might 
fail the first and only time it would be used the congressional 
office of technology assessment said 
the conclusions are part of a 2yearlong ota study that raises 
new questions about reagans program known formally the strategic 
defense initiative 
the strategic defense initiative organization in a statement 
said the report reflects a decidedly more constructive and 
balanced assessment than previous reports by ota 
but the statement disputed otas comments about computer 
software claiming the study failed to acknowledge the positive 
achievements and the real operating record of such systems as the 
safeguard ballistic missile defense which operated for a 10month 
period early in the last decade 
the ota study was publicly released despite the fact that the 
pentagon had refused to declassify three chapters dealing with ways 
the soviets could counter the american system 
when reagan announced his program in 1983 he proposed that it 
should be aimed at making nuclear weapons obsolete sdi officials 
have been overseeing research into a wide variety of futuristic 
technologies including lasers and beam weapons 
but in the past two years sdi officials and supporters of the 
program have been pushing for a less comprehensive phase one sdi 
system which could be started in the mid1990s the second and third 
phases of such a system would be constructed later 
last year the pentagon told congress that a phase one sdi system 
costing 75 billion to 150 billion could be deployed using a 
combination of groundbased rockets and spacebased rockets that 
would be parked in orbiting garages ready to fire at attacking 
soviet missiles 
but the soviets could attack such a system with antisatellite 
asat rockets using nucleartipped weapons the ota study said the 
soviets now have an operational asat system 
the soviet asats would pose a significant threat to all three 
defense system phases but particularly to the first two ota said 
such weapons deployed in quantity especially with multiple 
decoys to confuse the us system would threaten to degrade 
severely the performance of a first or secondphase sdi system 
the study said 
the study was the second ota report critical of reagans star 
wars plan other scientific reports have also questioned the 
feasibility of sdi goals 
the ota study also raised questions about the software that would 
be used to run the sdi computers other studies have raised 
questions about whether reliable software which would be far more 
complex than anything previously put together can be developed 
thomas h karas director of the ota study said there is a 
significant probability that the software would fail the first 
time it was used in a real situation 
the study noted that the nature of software and experience with 
large complex software systems indicate that there may always be 
irresolvable questions about how dependable the sdi programs 
would be and about the confidence the united states could place in 
dependability estimates 
in addition any attempt to realistically test the software could 
only be done by computer simulation and thus it would also be 
dependent on software karas said 
the study said there are no adequate models for the 
development production test and maintainance of software for 
fullscale missile defense systems 
karas said he didnt understand why public release of the three 
chapters had been refused by the pentagon they were so general that 
the soviets could not likely gain much military advantage from 
reading the material he said 
the study said it was difficult to come up with a precise 
degree of how well the us system could survive a soviet attack 
because that would depend on the tactics employed by each side and 
on the evitable uncertainties of battle 
the democraticcontrolled congress has consistently cut reagans 
requests for sdi spending the program is funded at 39 billion in 
the current fiscal year 
for the 1989 fiscal year beginning oct 1 the senate has voted 
46 billion while the house has approved 35 billion with a 
compromise to be worked out by a senatehouse conference committee 
reagan had sought 48 billion 
</TEXT>
