the bank board said rates on the most popular type of oneyear 
adjustablerate mortgages those with limits on how much the rate 
can increase also rose but not by as much they increased to 868 
percent in may up from 861 percent a month earlier 
james barth chief economist of the bank board said the 
percentage of mortgages with adjustable rates rose for the first 
time in five months to 53 percent in may up from 49 percent in 
april 
he attributed that to the widening of the spread between the two 
types of loans the gap grew for two months in a row from 169 
percent in march to 195 in may 
a separate weekly report by the federal home loan mortgage corp 
known as freddie mac show continued increases in fixedrate 
mortgages through may it said the average last week was 1058 
percent the same as the previous week but up from 1032 percent 
four weeks before 
freddie mac averages are lower than the bank boards because they 
do not include addon fees known as points which are paid by 
borrowers 
