<TEXT>
a soviet literary journal has taken a new look at 
vladimir i lenin saying the countrys founder tried to enforce 
tough economic policies by ordering executions and other tough 
measures that backfired 
in a 30page article in the may edition of novy mir new world 
vassily selyunin takes a more realistic look at lenins policies 
than the lenincandonowrong approach that has dominated official 
soviet news media for years 
selyunin said that in the first few years after the bolshevik 
revolution in 1917 lenin favored extremely harsh measures for 
putting the economy on track 
the extremes of force as we see spread boundlessly first it 
is undertaken for repression of opponents of the revolution then it 
is turned against potential enemies the red terror and finally it 
becomes a means for solving purely economic tasks selyunin wrote 
selyunin seemed to imply lenin laid the seeds for the abuses of 
power for which his successor josef v stalin has been condemned 
under kremlin leader mikhail s gorbachev historians are being 
encouraged to take a more honest look at the countrys past the 
result has been numerous press articles books and films blasting 
stalin who was responsible for the deaths of millions 
gorbachev attacked stalins economic policies under which the 
central government tightly controlled production and allowed little 
individual initiative 
the criticism extended to the era of stagnation under leonid 
i brezhnev who ruled the country from the early 1960s to 1982 but 
criticism of lenin has been offlimits 
the novy mir article says lenin was mistaken when he abolished 
all private property and created a system of forced labor camps 
lenin started to go astray in november 1917 when he declared 
that speculators were enemies of the people who should be 
shot when found according to selyunin speculation meant anything 
outside government trade 
lenin also advocated another harsh measure limiting peasant 
families to only the bread they needed to make it to the next 
harvest selyunin wrote the penalty for violation was a minimum 
10year jail term 
the author says lenin might be excused for some of the measures 
because the country was suffering severe hunger and destruction 
but selyunin wrote the harsh measures actually made the problems 
worse 
in january 1918 lenin supported a decree that increased prison 
space so class enemies could be incarcerated 
but lenin began to realize he was wrong and selyunin quotes him 
as saying the use of force was backfiring in that it was increasing 
civil unrest according to the article 
in march 1921 lenin made a midcourse correction and had a severe 
tax removed from peasants two months later he launched his new 
economic policy which allowed greater freedom in agriculture 
industry and trade 
selyunin credits this program with helping rid the country of 
bureaucracy which gorbachev has said is stifling some of his 
reforms 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

