whose torrid growth pace slowed markedly last year 
the california cooler beach party is history so is the sun 
country cooler spokesbear and actor bruce willis is missing from 
the action in new ads for seagrams wine coolers 
frank and ed are still pitching bartles amp jaymes coolers but it 
is uncertain who is going to be dreaming up new commercials for the 
folksy pair since the ad agency that created the brands fictional 
founding fathers quit 
something else is missing the fruit pulp that category pioneer 
california cooler had once brandished as evidence that it was the 
real stuff 
but the cooler makers are trying to liven things up with new 
flavors that they hope will get people to try their first cooler or 
give them another try 
seagrams the category leader plans eight flavors this year up 
from six last year bartles amp jaymes has doubled its list to four 
california cooler has five flavors up from four a year ago 
the big question facing the industry is whether coolers are a 
sustainable segment of the alcoholic beverage market or just a fad 
cooler sales tailed off in the second half of last summer prompting 
some analysts to speculate that consumers had tired of the 
sweettasting concoctions of fruit juice alcohol and water and were 
moving on to other drinks 
according to impact a publication of m shanken communications 
inc that tracks the wine business cooler shipments grew only 6 
percent to an estimated 726 million cases in 1987 industry 
executives said at an average price of about 350 for a fourpack 
that put the retail value of the category at about 15 billion 
but the 1987 growth rate was well below that in each of the 
previous three years in which the category rocketed from a few 
million cases in 1983 impact said the category grew 65 percent in 
1986 after tripling the previous year and soaring more than fivefold 
in 1984 when california cooler first encountered serious competition 
analysts said a slowdown in such growth was inevitable 
maybe for some people it was a fad said jon fredrikson 
president of gomberg fredrikson and associates wine industry 
consultants in san francisco but we believe there are hardcore 
winecooler drinkers out there who will continue to drink these 
products 
marvin shanken editor and publisher of impact said he also 
thought the category would survive and recently predicted it would 
amount to 133 million cases annually by the year 2000 
they each cited the categorys appeal to women drinkers and 
others who prefer an lightalcohol alternative to beer 
the shortterm outlook is unclear however shanken refused to 
estimate growth prospects for 1988 and fredrikson said the market 
may be flat 
william slone president of beverage media ltd a trade 
publisher said a lot of people have their fingers crossed but 
we havent seen any upturn in that market yet among retailers 
there is no expectation of any meaningful growth this year 
seagrams wine coolers from seagram beverage co of new york 
nosed ahead of bartles amp jaymes from eampj gallo winery of modesto 
calif last year according to impact california cooler from 
brownforman beverage co in louisville was third followed by sun 
country made by canandaigua wine co of a town by that name in new 
york 
seagram ended its twoyear association with willis the star of 
the television series moonlighting by mutual agreement this 
year said mark taxel a seagram executive he said willis helped 
seagram get to where we are in the market but our needs now are 
more complex 
he said seagram will use a series of celebrities for different 
flavors of its coolers including its new lime mist and seagrams 
extra new ads aired so far have featured actors steve guttenberg 
woody harrelson and anne archer 
bartles amp jaymes introduced a berry flavor in january and a new 
peach cooler in april which for the first time was heralded in an 
ad featuring frank and ed that was not created by gallos longtime 
agency hal riney amp partners of san francisco riney resigned last 
december and gallo spokesman dan solomon declined to discuss when a 
new fulltime agency may be retained 
california cooler had put the pulp in its citrus and orange 
coolers from the start in the early 1980s to make them look like the 
drinks that the todays coolers descended from mixtures of fruit 
juice and wine poured over huge blocks of ice in tubs on 
californias beaches in the 1960s its ads once featured songs from 
the era like louie louie and the bird is the word 
but both the beach party scenes and the 60s classics are gone 
from the new ads that use special effects to do things like 
transform a cherry into a bottle of its new wild cherry splash 
flavor 
john shastid an executive at brownforman said that while pulp 
had been an effective early addition to the drinks consumers now 
realize coolers contain real fruit juice and prefer coolers without 
pulp 
sun country dumped the pulp from its flavors too saying 
consumers were turned off by sediment at the bottom of the bottle 
it has also retired the ad approach that used celebrities in polar 
bear costumes to pitch its drink which now comes in eight flavors 
up from six 
the steamy ads for its new strawberry blush and wild jamaican 
rumflavored wine coolers made the abc and cbs networks blush 
executives demanded revisions in the ads that show scantilydressed 
men and women looking for relief from the heat and sun country 
complied 
