<TEXT>
a federal appeals court today set aside a 
contempt of court order against eastern airlines and an injunction 
barring the company from selling its northeast shuttle to another 
subsidiary of its parent texas air corp 
the us circuit court of appeals here ruled that us district 
judge john h pratt failed to make proper factual findings when he 
held eastern in contempt for taking steps to sell the profitable 
eastern air shuttle to a newly created subsidiary of texas air 
the deal was challenged by the international association of 
machinists and aerospace workers aflcio which contended the sale 
would violate the terms of a july 1987 injunction that pratt had 
issued in another labor dispute involving eastern 
the iam which represents 13000 eastern employees contends that 
texas air is trying to break up the airlines various components to 
weaken the power of the unions at the financially troubled carrier 
which texas air purchased in 1986 
a unanimous threejudge panel dissolved the injunction issued by 
pratt that bars eastern from proceeding with plans to sell the 
bostontonew yorktowashington shuttle to another subsidiary of 
texas air for 225 million 
it also set aside the modified injunction pratt issued barring 
the sale but gave the union 10 days to seek a temporary restraining 
order to stop the deal the court directed pratt to hold a factual 
hearing to determine if an injunction is warranted 
the court in an opinion by judge harry t edwards held that the 
july 1987 injunction pratt issued barring eastern from transferring 
6000 groundcrew workers into a subsidiary called airport ground 
services did not prohibit the shuttle deal 
thus eastern could not be held in contempt of the 1987 order for 
taking steps to transfer ownership of the shuttle 
in issuing the march order the district court did not weigh 
the tradiitonal equitable criteria nor did it make factual 
findings necessary to support the issuance of a new or modified 
injunction edwards wrote in an opinion joined by judges stephen 
williams and louis oberdorfer 
we appreciate the district courts concern that easterns 
announcement of the shuttle deal may have suggested a disregard for 
the spirit of the july injunction edwards wrote nonetheless 
this is an insufficient basis upon which to rest a finding of 
contempt where the district court has issued a new or modified 
injunction 
iam spokesman jim conley said the union had no immediate comment 
because its lawyers had not yet studied the decision 
eastern spokesman robin matell said we are pleased with the 
decision and are studying its implications 
