<TEXT>
a major international law firm said tuesday it 
will pay the salaries of 125 young lawyers each year who are are 
willing to work for the poor for two years after law school 
for five years beginning next june skadden arps will funnel 10 
million to qualified public service organizations to pay the 
salaries of skadden fellows 
the lawyers would provide legal services in civil law for poor 
people deprived of civil or human rights and who unlike persons 
accused of crime are not guaranteed counsel by the constitution 
the program also will instill in the lawyers a taste for pro bono 
public benefit work said peter p mullen executive partner of 
skadden arps slate meagher amp flom the firm 
the program will take the form of fellowships that pay about 
32500 a year plus fringe benefits comparable to secondyear 
salaries of federal judicial clerks said the announcement from 
skadden arps 
twentyfive skadden fellows will be named each year for the next 
five years and each will serve about two years 
there are many lawyers interested in and capable of dealing 
with the legal problems the disadvantaged encounter and there are 
many organizations that provide needy persons with legal services 
said mullen the problem has been that the organizations lack the 
funds to provide enough lawyers to fill the need much less at a 
reasonable salary 
a graduating lawyer applying for the fellowship must find a 
public service organization willing to employ him 
skadden arps founded 40 years ago has 177 partners and 675 
associates in seven major us cities and in london and tokyo 
</TEXT>
