<TEXT>
deliberations began tuesday in the case of a 
widower suing three tobacco companies over the lungcancer death of 
his wife who smoked cigarettes for 40 years 
the verdict in the 5yearold case one of a dozen cigarette 
liability cases ever to go to a jury could maintain the 22 
billion industrys unbeaten record in such suits or grant the first 
damages paid to smokers or their relatives 
the sixperson jury contains one smoker two former smokers and 
three people who have never smoked 
us district judge h lee sarokin read instructions on the law 
and claims that the panel must consider sarokin told five alternate 
jurors to remain on hand in case any jurors drop out 
the jurors deliberated for more than four hours before being 
dismissed for the night 
the panel must decide charges by antonio cipollone that lorillard 
inc liggett group inc and philip morris inc contributed to the 
death of his 58yearold wife rose in 1984 
cipollone contends the companies misled the public about the 
dangers of smoking through public relations advertising and 
inadequate research 
sarokin told the jurors they must decide four basic claims 
fraudulent misrepresentation and conspiracy to do so against each 
company and failure to warn and violation of a warranty against 
liggett 
the warning and warranty claims apply only to liggett because 
mrs cipollone smoked that companys cigarettes before warning 
labels were placed on cigarette packages and advertising in 1966 
courts have ruled that the labels preempt liability claims after 
that date 
sarokin framed the main charge as a claim that the companies 
fraudulently misrepresented material facts to consumers concerning 
significant health risks associated with cigarette smoking 
he said the jury has to determine five things that before 1966 
the company made a false representation that the company knew the 
representation was false that the company meant to deceive people 
that mrs cipollone believed the representation justifiably relied 
on it and was induced to continue smoking and that the 
representation was a proximate cause of her cancer and death 
the phrase proximate cause played a key role in the jury 
instructions sarokin said the panel has to consider whether the 
companies conduct before 1966 was a proximate cause of her smoking 
and then whether the smoking was a proximate cause of her death and 
disease 
the legal term means activity that naturally and probably led 
to and might have been expected to create the condition alleged 
sarokin wrote cipollone doesnt have to prove thatthe companies 
conduct was the only or even main reason why she smoked only that 
it was a substantial contributing factor 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

